The seminars are hosted at Harris Manchester College, University of Oxford, the University of Warwick and the British Academy.</gtr:piContribution><gtr:sector>Academic/University</gtr:sector><gtr:start>2015-01-01</gtr:start></gtr:collaborationOutput><gtr:collaborationOutput><gtr:collaboratingOrganisation>University of Bath</gtr:collaboratingOrganisation><gtr:country>United Kingdom of Great Britain &amp; Northern Ireland (UK)</gtr:country><gtr:description>Society for Educational Studies, Education, Security and Intelligence Studies seminar series grant</gtr:description><gtr:id>FF8A0592-76ED-4F6D-80E1-14A42310DCE3</gtr:id><gtr:impact>Education, Security and Intelligence Studies
Society for Education Studies
Seminar Series co-ordinated and facilitated by Dr Liam Gearon

Seminar 1
Theme
Education, Security and Intelligence Studies: Context-setting

Venue/ Date: Department of Education, University of Oxford, May 2016
Institution collaborating: University of Oxford 
Lead: Dr Liam Gearon, Associate Professor, Department of Education, and Senior Research Fellow, Harris Manchester College, University of Oxford

Rationale 
This opening seminar of the series will frame the interface of the seminar theme by (i) drawing upon special issue of the British Journal of Educational Studies on Education, Security and Intelligence Studies; and (ii) directly referencing the relationship between the Annual Seminar at the British Academy and the Seminar Series. 
 It will draw on UK and US perspectives: in the UK focusing on the implications of an emergent relationship between education, security and intelligence: in the UK by looking at issues such as Prevent, radicalisation and the responsibilities of educational institutions under the 2015 Counter-Terrorism and the Security Act; in the US, examination of the interface will focus on the rise of intelligence education in universities and the emergent International Association of Intelligence Education (IAIE). 


Seminar 2
Theme
Forensic and Open Source Intelligence

Venue/ Date: Nuffield College, University of Oxford/ June 2016 
Collaborating Institutions: Oxford Intelligence Group (OIG), Nuffield College, University of Oxford in association with Cranfield Defence and Security, Shrivenham

Dissemination, Marketing and Publication
? The seminar will be open to the host institution's student and staff body and external members of the seminar series 
? University website of host institution, other institutions involved in the seminar series and the Society for Educational Studies 
? Publication of proceedings: Co-edited volume Intelligence Education and International Security 

Rationale 
The work of the OIG is largely focused on bringing an interdisciplinary, social science approach to intelligence studies. Previous workshops convened by the OIG have included:
? 'Decoding the Human: Social Science Approaches to Cyber Security and Cyber Crime' (2015)
? 'Intelligence and Snowden - the consequences' (2014)
? 'Intelligence in Neutral Countries'(2013)
? 'Cyber Security and Social Science' (2012)
? 'The Ethics of National Security Intelligence' (2011)
As can be seen from these examples, the OIG is often at the forefront of new approaches in intelligence studies and, in keeping with this track record, the proposed workshop will make an early foray into the common themes that are to be found in forensic and open source intelligence, bringing sociology and forensic genetics research into the discussion. This would almost certainly be the first time such connections have been expressly made.

Dissemination, Marketing and Publication
? The seminar will be open to the host institution's student and staff body and external members of the seminar series 
? University website of host institution, other institutions involved in the seminar series and the Society for Educational Studies 
? Publication of proceedings: Co-edited volume Intelligence Education and International Security 

Seminar 3
Security and Intelligence Studies and Higher Education

Venues/ Dates: University of Buckingham/ University of East London, July 2016
Institutions collaborating: University of Buckingham and University of East London

Rationale 
These linked seminars at the University of East London and the University of Buckingham consider the relationship between universities and national security. They draw on experts from the UK and Germany and across academic and security services.

Seminar 3a: University of Buckingham
Security and Intelligence Studies and Higher Education
This seminar will attempt to initiate an assessment of how security issues may in part be framing the culture of HE in the UK in three areas: (i) Research and teaching into security-related questions in HE: disciplinary challenges to social science research (ii) The practical consequences of government 'Prevent' policy for teaching and learning culture in UK HEIs (whether 'Prevent' inhibits the teaching of modules on terrorism and extremism, for example, and the extent to which HEIs should feel oblige to host non-academic political or religious events (iii) The impact of government security policy on HE culture in the UK: that, for example, the unintended consequences of legislation to contain Islamist jihadism may be the breeding a new kind of anti-government culture amongst academics and their students, bringing together groups with different and often conflicting aims (e.g. 'conservative' Islamic thinking with gender extremism), united in their opposition to being squeezed out of HE culture. 
 

Seminar 3b: University of East London
Universities and security research: a fragile relationship?

Universities are implicated in the business of National Security. As producers of security research and technologies, centres of student and academic debate and repositories of knowledge, Higher Education Institutions are sometimes seen to be key to this endeavour. At certain times in history the link between Universities and National Security institutions has been strong but there are always tensions in this relationship. These joint seminars will consider the fragility of the relationship between universities and national security considering the relation between academic expertise and the security state, student radicalisation and freedom of speech, the politicisation of campus life and the agenda of research funders. They draw on experts from the UK and Germany


Dissemination, Marketing and Publication
? The seminar will be open to the host institutions' student and staff body and external members of the seminar series 
? University website of host institution, other institutions involved in the seminar series and the Society for Educational Studies 
? Publication of proceedings: Co-edited volume Intelligence Education and International Security 

Seminar 4
Theme
Security Studies and the Humanities

Venue/ Date: Royal United Service Institute, Westminster, London, September 2016
Institutions collaborating: Royal United Service Institute (RUSI)

Rationale 
The field of security studies has widened and diversified in recent years to incorporate disciplines from the 'hard' sciences and the social sciences. In sub-fields such as terrorism studies, social science disciplines such as psychology and political science have made particularly strong contributions - so strong that the humanities are in danger of being eclipsed. This seminar would seek to explore and promote the contribution being made by researchers and teachers in three disciplines - history, literary studies, and cultural studies. It will aim to encourage a greater and more confident contribution from the humanities to 'real world' security problems. 

Dissemination, Marketing and Publication
? The seminar will be open to the host institution's student and staff body and external members of the seminar series 
? University website of host institution, other institutions involved in the seminar series and the Society for Educational Studies 
? Publication of proceedings: Co-edited volume Intelligence Education and International Security 

Seminar 5
Theme
Securitising Education to Prevent Terrorism?
Freedom of Speech and National Security 

Venue/ Date: University of Bath, October 2016
Institutions collaborating: University of Bath - Department of Politics, Languages and International Studies with Department of Education 

Rationale 
This seminar examines the growing relationship between security and education, particularly in the light of the UK government's Prevent Duty that seeks to tackle radicalisation in a variety of milieus, including universities. However, rather than seeing this process as being merely one-way, through a so-called securitisation of education (in the parlance of the Copenhagen School of International Relations), what is explored here is the dialectic between these two spheres.
 Dissemination, Marketing and Publication
? The seminar will be open to the host institution's student and staff body and external members of the seminar series 
? University website of host institution, other institutions involved in the seminar series and the Society for Educational Studies 
? Publication of proceedings: Co-edited volume Intelligence Education and International Security</gtr:impact><gtr:outcomeId>56d55abc786ea9.28678738-4</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:partnerContribution>Education, Security and Intelligence Studies
Society for Education Studies
Seminar Series co-ordinated and facilitated by Dr Liam Gearon

Seminar 1
Theme
Education, Security and Intelligence Studies: Context-setting

Venue/ Date: Department of Education, University of Oxford, May 2016
Institution collaborating: University of Oxford 
Lead: Dr Liam Gearon, Associate Professor, Department of Education, and Senior Research Fellow, Harris Manchester College, University of Oxford

Rationale 
This opening seminar of the series will frame the interface of the seminar theme by (i) drawing upon special issue of the British Journal of Educational Studies on Education, Security and Intelligence Studies; and (ii) directly referencing the relationship between the Annual Seminar at the British Academy and the Seminar Series. 
 It will draw on UK and US perspectives: in the UK focusing on the implications of an emergent relationship between education, security and intelligence: in the UK by looking at issues such as Prevent, radicalisation and the responsibilities of educational institutions under the 2015 Counter-Terrorism and the Security Act; in the US, examination of the interface will focus on the rise of intelligence education in universities and the emergent International Association of Intelligence Education (IAIE). 


Seminar 2
Theme
Forensic and Open Source Intelligence

Venue/ Date: Nuffield College, University of Oxford/ June 2016 
Collaborating Institutions: Oxford Intelligence Group (OIG), Nuffield College, University of Oxford in association with Cranfield Defence and Security, Shrivenham

Dissemination, Marketing and Publication
? The seminar will be open to the host institution's student and staff body and external members of the seminar series 
? University website of host institution, other institutions involved in the seminar series and the Society for Educational Studies 
? Publication of proceedings: Co-edited volume Intelligence Education and International Security 

Rationale 
The work of the OIG is largely focused on bringing an interdisciplinary, social science approach to intelligence studies. Previous workshops convened by the OIG have included:
? 'Decoding the Human: Social Science Approaches to Cyber Security and Cyber Crime' (2015)
? 'Intelligence and Snowden - the consequences' (2014)
? 'Intelligence in Neutral Countries'(2013)
? 'Cyber Security and Social Science' (2012)
? 'The Ethics of National Security Intelligence' (2011)
As can be seen from these examples, the OIG is often at the forefront of new approaches in intelligence studies and, in keeping with this track record, the proposed workshop will make an early foray into the common themes that are to be found in forensic and open source intelligence, bringing sociology and forensic genetics research into the discussion. This would almost certainly be the first time such connections have been expressly made.

Dissemination, Marketing and Publication
? The seminar will be open to the host institution's student and staff body and external members of the seminar series 
? University website of host institution, other institutions involved in the seminar series and the Society for Educational Studies 
? Publication of proceedings: Co-edited volume Intelligence Education and International Security 

Seminar 3
Security and Intelligence Studies and Higher Education

Venues/ Dates: University of Buckingham/ University of East London, July 2016
Institutions collaborating: University of Buckingham and University of East London

Rationale 
These linked seminars at the University of East London and the University of Buckingham consider the relationship between universities and national security. They draw on experts from the UK and Germany and across academic and security services.

Seminar 3a: University of Buckingham
Security and Intelligence Studies and Higher Education
This seminar will attempt to initiate an assessment of how security issues may in part be framing the culture of HE in the UK in three areas: (i) Research and teaching into security-related questions in HE: disciplinary challenges to social science research (ii) The practical consequences of government 'Prevent' policy for teaching and learning culture in UK HEIs (whether 'Prevent' inhibits the teaching of modules on terrorism and extremism, for example, and the extent to which HEIs should feel oblige to host non-academic political or religious events (iii) The impact of government security policy on HE culture in the UK: that, for example, the unintended consequences of legislation to contain Islamist jihadism may be the breeding a new kind of anti-government culture amongst academics and their students, bringing together groups with different and often conflicting aims (e.g. 'conservative' Islamic thinking with gender extremism), united in their opposition to being squeezed out of HE culture. 
 

Seminar 3b: University of East London
Universities and security research: a fragile relationship?

Universities are implicated in the business of National Security. As producers of security research and technologies, centres of student and academic debate and repositories of knowledge, Higher Education Institutions are sometimes seen to be key to this endeavour. At certain times in history the link between Universities and National Security institutions has been strong but there are always tensions in this relationship. These joint seminars will consider the fragility of the relationship between universities and national security considering the relation between academic expertise and the security state, student radicalisation and freedom of speech, the politicisation of campus life and the agenda of research funders. They draw on experts from the UK and Germany


Dissemination, Marketing and Publication
? The seminar will be open to the host institutions' student and staff body and external members of the seminar series 
? University website of host institution, other institutions involved in the seminar series and the Society for Educational Studies 
? Publication of proceedings: Co-edited volume Intelligence Education and International Security 

